\begin_layout Standard
Consider the KCBS scenario, i.e.
 an experimental scenario which is specified by the events 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},e_{2}\dots e_{5}$
\end_inset

 whose exclusivity is given by a 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

-cycle exclusivity graph.
 Suppose we obtain the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}\dots p_{5}$
\end_inset

 experimentally (and ensure that they correspond to sharp measurements).
 We already saw that if these values nearly saturate the quantum bound for
 the KCBS non-contextuality inequality, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}p_{i}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{5}\approx2.236\dots$
\end_inset

, then we know that all quantum realisations corresponding to the experimentally
 obtained probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 are almost equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\text{KCBS}},\{\Pi_{i}^{\text{KCBS}}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

, up to a global isometry.
 To be more precise, consider any arbitrary quantum realisation given by
 a pure state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and rank one projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Pi_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}p_{i}=2+\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 It was shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bharti2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that then, there exists an isometry 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert V\Pi_{i}V^{\dagger}-\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS}\right\Vert _{F}\le\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\epsilon})\label{eq:projKish}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2\dots5\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \rho-\rho^{{\rm KCBS}}\right\Vert _{F}\le\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\epsilon})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert A\right\Vert _{F}:={\rm tr}\left(\sqrt{A^{\dagger}A}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Verify this:] This result is stronger than the self-testing results which
 are usually stated for Bell non-locality, in the following sense.
 Typically, one is only able to make statements about the action of the
 projectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 on the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (see, for instance, ...).
 EDIT: This was wrong; here we assume the projectors are orthogonal which
 can't ever be deduced with certainty from observing just the statistics.
 Maybe some part of the Hilbert space is never accessed by the states in
 question.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Despite this, without the constant hidden in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:projKish"
plural "false"
caps "true"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, one cannot obtain a robustness curve and thus one cannot apply this in
 practice.
 In this work, we remedy this problem, taking inspiration from the Bell
 self-testing approach.
 To this end, we give a slightly different statement: we show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{5}\mathcal{F}(V\Pi_{i}\rho\Pi_{i}V^{\dagger},\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS}\rho^{\KCBS}\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS})+\mathcal{F}(V\rho V^{\dagger},\rho^{\KCBS})\ge f(\epsilon)\label{eq:lowerbound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(A,B):={\rm tr}\sqrt{\left|A^{1/2}B^{1/2}\right|}$
\end_inset

, we only require 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 to be projectors (such that 
\begin_inset Formula $[\Pi_{i},\Pi_{j}]=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)$
\end_inset

 is an edge of the exclusivity graph) and allow 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 to be a mixed state.
 The advantage is that we are able to express 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 as a hierarchy of semi-definite programmes and compute lower bounds explicitly.
 While we state our result for the KCBS inequality, it readily extends to
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-cycle scenario.
 [TODO: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 cannot be shown to be independent of the individual 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

s, then we must skip it].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that while the result due to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bharti2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 only applies to rank one projectors and pure states, we can not make this
 assumption in our approach.
 This is because we are minimising over the set of all possible quantum
 realisations.
 But it is known that [VERIFY/GIVE AN ARGUMENT] for every quantum realisation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho',\{\Pi_{i}'\}$
\end_inset

 one can find a quantum realisation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho,\{\Pi_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are projectors (in a possibly larger space) which yields the same experimental
 outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here, we wish to be more quantitative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We want to know that given a certain value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}p_{i}$
\end_inset

, how close is every possible quantum realisation, given that it is consistent
 with the observed statistics 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

, to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\KCBS},\left\{ \Pi_{i}^{\KCBS}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

.
 CLAIM (TODO: Kishor must check this): It turns out that this closeness
 depends only on the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and not on the individual values 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

.
 The robustness curve, simply represents this closeness of quantum realisations
 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{5}p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We, in fact, satisfy ourselves with an upper bound on this measure of closeness.
 We now define the measure of closeness we use in this article.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As a measure of closeness between two quantum realisations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{A},\{\Pi_{i}^{A}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{B},\{\Pi_{i}^{B}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

, we use simply a sum of fidelities of the state and measurement settings,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}\left((\rho^{A},\{\Pi_{i}^{A}\}_{i=1}^{5}),(\rho^{B},\{\Pi_{i}^{B}\}_{i=1}^{5})\right):=\mathcal{F}\left(\rho^{A},\rho^{B}\right)+\sum_{i=1}^{5}\mathcal{F}(\Pi_{i}^{A}\rho^{A}\Pi_{i}^{A},\Pi_{i}^{B}\rho^{B}\Pi_{i}^{B}).
\]

\end_inset

Clearly, when both the states and the measurement settings are equal, the
 result is 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We now proceed more formally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
General description (explain importance)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider any state and measurement system, which we henceforth call a configurat
ion, that is consistent with the observed data.
 A robustness curve is a lower bound on the fidelity of any such configuration
 with the ideal configuration.
 The curve is a relation between the fidelity and the value of the KCBS
 expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More formally, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{min}\mathcal{F}\left(\left(\left|\psi^{\text{ideal}}\right\rangle ,\left\{ \Pi_{i}^{\text{ideal}}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}\right),\left(\left|\psi^{\text{cand}}\right\rangle ,\left\{ \Pi_{i}^{\text{cand}}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 subject to the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi^{\text{cand}}\right\rangle ,\left\{ \Pi_{i}^{\text{cand}}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 satisfy the experimental statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fidelity= fidelity of state plus fidelity of measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finding a lower-bound is non-trivial.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overall Strategy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An ideal KCBS configuration
\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider a three-dimensional Hilbert space spanned by the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\left|0\right\rangle ,\left|1\right\rangle ,\left|2\right\rangle \}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|u_{l}\right\rangle :=\cos\theta\left|0\right\rangle +\sin\theta\sin\phi_{l}\left|1\right\rangle +\sin\theta\cos\phi_{l}\left|2\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{l}:=l\pi(n-1)/n$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le l\le n$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left|\psi^{\KCBS}\right\rangle  & :=\left|0\right\rangle \\
\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS} & :=\left|u_{i}\right\rangle \left\langle u_{i}\right|.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TODO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\strikeout on
Verify if we require that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}\Pi_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 or that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr[\Pi_{i}\Pi_{j}\rho]=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr[\Pi_{i}\Pi_{j}\Pi_{k}\rho]$
\end_inset

 (by assumption; write clearly in the previous section); [status: we handled
 this already]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Update: say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\left|\psi\right\rangle \left\langle \psi\right|$
\end_inset

 without loss of generality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may restate the aforesaid discussion more symbolically as lower bounding
 the value of the following objective function: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F:=\min_{\rho,\{\Pi_{i}\}}\max_{V}\left[\sum_{i=1}^{5}\mathcal{F}(V\Pi_{i}\rho\Pi_{i}V^{\dagger},\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS}\rho^{\KCBS}\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS})+\mathcal{F}(V\rho V^{\dagger},\rho^{\KCBS})\right]\label{eq:fidelity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho,\{\Pi_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 is a quantum realisation
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
note that we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are projectors as the measurements are assumed to be sharp experimentally
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an isometry from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}^{\KCBS}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 from the space on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho,\{\Pi_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 act/are defined to that where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{\KCBS},\{\Pi_{i}^{\KCBS}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

 act/are defined.
 At the broadest level, the idea is to drop the maximization over 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and replace it with a particular isometry 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 which is expressed in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho,\{\Pi_{i}\}_{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, as we shall see, the expression for the fidelity appears as a sum
 of terms of the following form.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 be a word created from the letters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbb{I},\Pi_{1},\Pi_{2}\dots\Pi_{5},\hat{P}\}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}^{\dagger}\hat{P}=\mathbb{I}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}^{2}=\Pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{i}\Pi_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,j)\in E(G)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 are exclusive
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We introduced 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{P}$
\end_inset

 for completeness; its role is explained later.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The fidelity is a linear combination of these words, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\min_{\left\{ \left\langle w\right\rangle \right\} }\sum_{w}\alpha_{w}\left\langle w\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tr[w\rho]=:\left\langle w\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, subject to the constraint that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\left\langle w\right\rangle \}_{w}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a quantum realisation.
 The advantage of casting the problem in this form is that one can now construct
 an NPA-like hierarchy.
 The idea is simple to state.
 Treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left\langle w\right\rangle \right\} _{w}$
\end_inset

 as a vector.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the set of all such vectors which correspond to a quantum realisation (of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ p_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{5}$
\end_inset

).
 It turns out that one can impose constraints on words with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 letters, for instance.
 Under these constraints, denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 the set that is obtained.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}\supseteq Q$
\end_inset

 for it may contain vectors which don't correspond to the quantum realisation.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be characterised using semi-definite programming constraints (which
 in turn means they are efficiently computable).
 Intuitively, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{k\to\infty}Q_{k}=Q$
\end_inset

.
 Further, it is also clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\min_{\{\left\langle w\right\rangle \}_{w}\in Q}\sum_{w}\alpha_{w}\left\langle w\right\rangle \ge\min_{\left\{ \left\langle w\right\rangle \right\} _{w}\in Q_{k}}\sum_{w}\alpha_{w}\left\langle w\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as we are minimising over a larger set on the right hand side.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the following sections, we delineate the aforementioned procedure, including
 the isometry 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, in detail.
 
\end_layout

